In Java, Integer inherits from Number`(java.lang.Number)`, so intuitively, anything that is an Integer`(java.lang.Integer)` is also a number, but what that article points out is that with generics it does not work that way, because considering that example, you could end up putting a float (which is a Number) into a `List&lt;Integer&gt;`, which is illegal because a float is not an integer.

